===Verb===
{{en-verb|hand|hands|handed|handing}}

#{{transitive}} To give, pass, or transmit with the hand; as
#: ''he '''handed''' them the letter.''
#{{transitive}} To lead, guide, or assist with the hand; to conduct
#: ''to '''hand''' a lady into a carriage.''
#{{transitive}} {{obsolete}} To manage; as, I '''hand''' my [[oar]]. — [[Prior]]
#{{transitive}} {{obsolete}} To seize; to lay hands on. — Shakespeare
#{{transitive}} {{rare}} To pledge by the hand; to handfast.
#{{transitive}} {{nautical}} To [[furl]]; — said of a sail. — [[Totten]]
#{{intransitive}} {{obsolete}} To [[cooperate|coöperate]]. — [[Massinger]]

====Derived terms====
*To [[hand down]]: to transmit in succession, as from father to son, or from predecessor to successor; as, fables are handed down from age to age; to forward to the proper officer (the decision of a higher court); as, the Clerk of the Court of Appeals handed down its decision.
*To [[hand over]]: to yield control of; to surrender; to deliver up.

